  "prompt": "What is the difference between Psychology, Psychiatry & Psychoanalysis?",
  "response": "Here's a breakdown of the differences between Psychology, Psychiatry, and Psychoanalysis:\n\nPsychology:\n- Study of human behavior, mental processes, and emotions\n- Focuses on understanding mental functioning and human interactions\n- Practitioners (Psychologists) have doctoral degrees (PhD or PsyD)\n- Provide therapy, counseling, and psychological assessments\n- Cannot prescribe medication\n- Work in various settings like clinics, schools, research, and private practice\n\nPsychiatry:\n- Medical specialty focused on mental health and mental disorders\n- Practitioners (Psychiatrists) are medical doctors (MD or DO)\n- Can diagnose mental health conditions\n- Can prescribe medication\n- Treat mental health through medication management and therapy\n- Often work in hospitals, clinics, and private practices\n- Typically handle more severe mental health conditions\n\nPsychoanalysis:\n- Specific therapeutic approach developed by Sigmund Freud\n- Focuses on exploring unconscious thoughts and past experiences\n- Involves deep, long-term therapy sessions\n- Aims to uncover underlying psychological conflicts\n- Analyzes how past experiences shape current behavior\n- Typically conducted by specially trained psychologists or psychiatrists\n- Less common and more time-intensive than other therapeutic approaches\n\nEach discipline plays a unique role in understanding and treating mental health.",
